entry.title: [color] Fix ThemeChanged() propagation for default BrowserFrames
entry.content:
Currently BrowserFrame::UserChangedTheme() relies on

RegenerateFrameOnThemeChange() to implicitly call into

ThemeChanged().



However this is a flawed assumption as Widget::FrameTypeChanged()

may not necessarily call ThemeChanged() as assumed. This can occur

for default frames backed by a DesktopWindowTreeHostPlatform [1].



In general this is a pretty poor assumption to make,

FrameTypeChanged() serves to notify the Widget the frame type has

changed and nothing about the API indicates a ThemeChanged()

notification is expected.



This CL introduces a Widget observer that calls ThemeChanged() if

the FrameTypeChanged() did not. This makes the theme propagation

logic more resilient to future changes and avoids redundant

notifications.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:ui/views/widget/desktop_aura/desktop_window_tree_host_platform.cc;l=706;drc=78b5e4a98fc825dc083717cb96ae4d7441a53877

entry.title: Rationalize the behavior of SupportsFocus, Is{keybd|mouse}Focusable
entry.content:
This CL cleans up three functions in Element:



- SupportsFocus: true if the element is *capable* of being focused. An

element supports focus if, e.g. it has a tabindex attribute, or it is

editable, or other conditions. Note that the element might *support*

focus while not *being focusable*, for example if the element is

disconnected from the document.



- IsMouseFocusable: true if the element SupportsFocus() *and* is

currently focusable using the mouse.



- IsKeyboardFocusable: true if the element IsMouseFocusable(), *and*

is currently focusable using the keyboard.



Note that each method is a subset of the one above it, by

construction.



This also adds IsScrollableContainerThatShouldBeKeyboardFocusable(),

which returns true for scrollers that should be made keyboard focusable if the feature flag for that behavior is enabled.



This also adds a `DocumentLifecycle::DisallowTransitionScope` to

make sure SupportsFocus() does not update the rendering lifecycle.



Note crbug.com/1474971 and the new baselines for the

video-playback-speed-menu.html test. That focus ring was there due

to a confluence of weirdness in the media controls code, and that

will need to be tackled separately, if desired. The new behavior

might also be ok.



Note that accessibility code is using `SupportsFocus()` to mean

`IsFocusable()`, but prior to this CL, there were cases in which

`SupportsFocus()` returned false and yet `IsFocusable()` returned

true. That has been fixed in this CL everywhere except a11y code,

which still uses `SupportsFocus()`. In addition, to avoid breaking

a11y code, `SupportsFocus()` is still not calling the new

`IsScrollableContainerThatShouldBeKeyboardFocusable()` method, which

means for focusable scrollers, SupportsFocus will be `false` while

`IsFocusable()` will be true. This will be fixed in a followup

CL [2].



This patch borrows heavily from [1].



[1] https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4518938

[2] https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4813829

entry.title: Annotate ExperimentalAsh dangling pointers [13/N]
entry.content:
Context:

--------

@bartekn is going to remove the `ExperimentalAsh` raw_ptr annotation:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4767965/1

This was a performance experiment to enable/disable MiraclePtr on a

subset of new pointers added for ChromeOS ash (non-lacros).



Before removing it, he needs to enable it by default in code. Enabling

MiraclePtr for them, causes the DanglingPointerDetector to be enforced.

To pass the CQ, we need to annotate pre-existing dangling pointer with

`DanglingUntriaged`. After enabling ExperimentalAsh feature, it won't be

allowed anymore for those pointers to become dangling.



How this patch was made:

------------------------



1. Enable the `PartitionAllocBackupRefPtrForAsh` feature.

2. Instrument raw_ptr using:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4506773/50

3. Run the CQ, and retrieve the list of location.

4. Manually rewrite every dangling pointers from the list.

entry.title: Lacros proxy tracker: Send extension metadata on extension loaded
entry.content:
The Lacros proxy tracker sends updates to Ash with metadata describing

the extension which is controlling the proxy pref. Ash uses this

metadata to populate the network settings UI.



There are a few cases where the Lacros proxy tracker receives proxy pref

updates but the extension which is controlling the proxy is not yet

loaded:

- A new Chrome session is started, where the extension has set the proxy

pref in a previous session;

- Ash to Lacros profile migration;

- Disabling and then enabling an extension which is controlling the

proxy.



This happens because the ExtensionPrefs KeyedService is parsing the extension-set pref values from the user pref kExtensions and setting it into the extensions pref store before the extension are loaded. The user pref kExtensions is stored in the Preferences file and read from disk when the PrefService is created.



For the last two cases, Ash never receives the extension metadata.



This CL adds an observer for RegistryEvents in the Lacros proxy tracker

to retry sending the extension metadata when the extension is ready.



Bug: b/293845404, b/290184836

entry.title: views: Handle ET_MOUSE_ENTERED in Widget and RootView
entry.content:
When running interactive_ui_tests on Linux ozone/wayland, it can happen

that the compositor only sends a "mouse enter" event that isn't

immediately followed by a "mouse motion" event. This results in only a

ET_MOUSE_ENTERED event being sent to Widget. However, both Widget and

RootView currently don't handle this type of event, which can lead to

test failures (see the related bug for more details).



We should handle enter events the same as other event types. This CL

implements this handling by reusing the code that handles ET_MOUSE_MOVED

events, because we need to set up `mouse_move_handler_` and synthesize

enter and exit events in the same way; the only difference is that we

don't send an ET_MOUSE_MOVED event to `mouse_move_handler_` when we're

handling an ET_MOUSE_ENTERED event.



Fixed: 1472995
